rComments: Wasn't the worst prof I've ever had, but as others say: too smart to be teaching CHM132. Tests aren't hard at face value, but because he sucks at teaching concepts to first years in they become difficult. But they are pretty much identical to the practice ones he posts! I recommend watching youtube videos and reading the textbook in your own time.

I did not find him as bad as people made him out to be. He was good at explaining concepts and did lots of review examples in class leading up to the midterms. Midterms and final were fair (2nd midterm was tricky), but the assignments on brightspace were good practice. The practice midterms were also very similar to the actual tests. You got this!

Everyone's right that this prof is rude. I had to reach out to the vice-dean to get him to answer me when I was severely ill for 2 weeks. But he's so damn good at teaching that I'd still take his course again (just, you know, avoid needing to talk to him). He explains concepts very thoroughly and keeps making links, he literally made me enjoy orgo.
Too smart for first year organic chem. Gets frustrated easily if you don't know the answers. One thing that was good is his midterms were almost identical to the practice ones.

DON'T TAKE HIS CLASS. Organic chem is already hard on its own but prof Organ will make you want to cry after every class. He calls the class stupid and if NO ONE can answer the question, who do you think is the problem? His tests are fair but when the prof sucks and makes you wanna jump off a bridge, the course isn't very enjoyable.
too smart to be teaching a first year course.

His midterms were exactly like the practice ones. You know what to expect. Hes super inclusive in his lectures and if you pay attention its really easy to understand everything. Good idea to catch up on ur old Chem knowledge though Or else you wont understand anything
No homeworks assigned, he doesn't mention what will be in the midterms in his syllabus, and he is not organized. I dropped his class.
Organ is a solid prof. I found the lectures hard, but go over the textbook questions and the assignments. It's very helpful to review the lessons on the same day it was thought.

Avoid. He's too smart to teach a first year organic chem course. He gets frustrated easily, is VERY rude in emails, and boring in lectures. If you email him a question, he usually just responds "check the lecture", which is impractical, especially if you have already watched the lecture and don't understand, or have an exam. Tests were fair though.
teacherRatingTags: ['Test heavy', 'Get ready to read', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: Organ is great. Organic chem is overall content heavy and tough but I found that Organ's exams well reflected the material he taught in class. Lectures weren't super well structured but you can tell how knowledgeable he is. Unmute and ask your questions in class!

His lecturing often felt awkward. He also spoke as if lots of the material was review even though this was our first ever organic chemistry course. He sounded impatient when answering students' questions. Tests were challenging but not unreasonable and it was possible to receive part marks on many questions.

I personally found it hard to focus during the lectures with it being online perhaps because Organ was boring or because I have a short attention span. Still managed to do decent in the course by doing the assignments and textbook questions. I heard other profs (Oglive & Newman) classes were easier but i enjoyed Organ and he cares about students

Overall a solid professor, the course content is not easy but he explained things very well and gave students a chance to succeed. If you study hard, do the assignments and the textbook questions, you should do pretty well.

Dr. Organ is clearly a very smart man. I can assume the other people on this site probably did not do well because they did not listen to his advice on studying and doing the practice problems from the text book. I wrote the final today and it was clearly text book heavy. He is always willing to have extra office hours to answer questions.
Most boring lecturer ever. Took away the little bit of interest I had in organic chem.

Its best to avoid him. He doesn't give feedback on the exams so we can't learn from our mistakes, or even identify our mistakes sometimes. Tests are quite straightforward and sometimes directly taken from previous years.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Get ready to read', 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: He is knowledgable, but not the best lecturer. He assumes we already know everything when in reality, most of our high schools only taught us nomenclature for orgo chem, and mine didn't even do that. He can be rude sometimes. His tests are very challenging. His lectures are quite boring, I self-studied the whole course.

The lectures were very boring and confusing. He speaks very monotone and sometimes it felt like he was assuming we already knew what he was talking about, even though it was orgo 1 and all they teach you in high school is nomenclature, so no one had real prior knowledge. Luckily, the textbook is great so I was able to teach myself.

CHM1321 is a weed-out course, so it is hard enough. Dr. Organ makes it even worse. He is incredibly rude in his emails and assumes that if you don't come to the live lectures, you don't pay attention at all (I live in a different time zone so can't be live). His tests are hard and he teaches as if we already know all the topics. Avoid him.

He is very knowledgable but I don't think he understands that we are only first years and have never really done organic chemistry. He lectures as if the course should be review so I felt I had to self-study most of the time. If you don't have an extremely thorough understanding it will be hard to pass. Only a quiz, two midterms, and a final.

This was his first time teaching a 1st year course and I think he forgot that a lot of us have never seen organic chem before. Gets upset easily, not understanding of the struggles of online uni. Ex: right before the midterm, some students said their internet was bad due to the thunderstorm. He replied "the internet's fine here at the university.."

Will be very critical if you don't have a thorough understanding on the material *when you go to him for help on getting a more thorough understanding on the material* But otherwise at least does his job as a lecturer.

All his slides are based on the textbook, so I highly recommend reading through textbook information if things are unclear. Midterms were challenging but not impossible. Again, your textbook is your best friend, practice the textbook questions!!!
